# Writing Style — Social Media

This rule captures Michael Loizias's authentic social media voice, derived from analysis of 31 LinkedIn posts spanning personal, health, business, and industry commentary.

---

## Core Voice Characteristics

### Tone
- **Direct and unvarnished** — states opinions plainly, doesn't hedge or soften unnecessarily
- **Reflective but not sentimental** — shares personal experiences with purpose, not for sympathy
- **Grounded in reality** — practical, experienced, speaks from lived knowledge
- **Confident without arrogance** — owns achievements and mistakes equally
- **Occasionally blunt** — willing to call out bad practices, poor behaviour, or industry failings

### Emotional Register
- Measured, even when discussing difficult topics (illness, near-death, surgery)
- Allows vulnerability but frames it constructively — always a lesson or forward motion
- Gratitude is expressed simply, not effusively
- Frustration is channelled into critique or calls to action, not venting

---

## Structural Patterns

### Opening Lines
- Often starts with context or a statement of fact, not a hook or question
- Rarely uses clickbait or "engagement bait" openers
- May start with a personal admission or reflection

**Examples:**
- "For the first time in my professional career, I will be using my real surname."
- "The last 6 weeks have been an absolute rollercoaster for myself and my family."
- "I'm confident in saying that the last couple of years have been some of the most challenging periods for our industry."
- "One thing that has really struck me since diving into the tech world is the difference in culture."

### Middle / Body
- Uses short paragraphs (1-3 sentences typically)
- Lists are used for clarity, not padding — usually actionable or concrete
- Includes specific numbers, names, timeframes (e.g. "2 hours each way", "lost 20kg", "£100,000 mistake")
- Balances personal narrative with broader relevance or takeaway
- Often includes a turning point or contrast (before/after, expectation/reality)

### Closing Lines
- Frequently ends with a forward-looking statement or call to action
- May include a signature phrase: **"Keep Moving Forward"** or **"Get up and keep moving forward"**
- Sometimes ends with a rhetorical question inviting reflection
- Tags relevant companies/people at the end, not inline

**Examples:**
- "The story continues, just in a new direction."
- "Sometimes the right thing is not strategic. It is just human."
- "Wonder where we'll be in 5 more years?!"
- "Let's rise to the challenge and make those changes happen."

---

## Language & Word Choice

### Use
- Plain English — no jargon unless industry-specific and necessary
- First person ("I", "we") — personal and direct
- Concrete language — specific examples, not abstractions
- Occasional British colloquialisms ("off my rocket", "dodgy stomach", "a punt")
- Light humour where appropriate, especially self-deprecating

### Avoid
- Buzzwords ("synergy", "leverage", "ecosystem", "disrupt")
- Excessive qualifiers ("incredibly", "absolutely", "truly" — used sparingly, not stacked)
- Hollow corporate phrases ("excited to announce", "thrilled to share" — used occasionally but not as default)
- Overly polished or sanitised language
- Emoji overload — uses 1-2 max per post, often none
- Hyphens, en dashes, and em dashes. This includes hyphenated compound words (e.g. "real-time", "high-quality"), em dashes for parenthetical phrases (e.g. "the system — which works well — is live"), and en dashes. These are clear signs of AI generated content. Use commas, full stops, or rephrase instead

### Punctuation & Formatting
- Uses ellipsis (...) occasionally for pacing or trailing thought
- Bold text for emphasis on key phrases (LinkedIn formatting)
- Bullet points for lists, numbered lists for sequential items or lessons
- No excessive exclamation marks — uses them sparingly for genuine emphasis

---

## Thematic Patterns

### Personal / Health Posts
- Shares difficult experiences openly but with purpose
- Frames illness/adversity as context for change, not as complaint
- Acknowledges support from others without being saccharine
- Often includes practical advice or encouragement for others in similar situations

### Business / Milestone Posts
- Pride in team and company growth, attributed to collective effort
- Specific achievements cited (revenue, headcount, properties delivered)
- Acknowledges hard work and sacrifice required
- Often reflects on journey from humble beginnings

### Industry Commentary
- Critical of poor practices — calls out clients, consultants, contractors directly
- Advocates for fairness, reasonable terms, quality over cheapness
- Draws on personal experience as evidence
- Poses questions to prompt reflection, not just to provoke

### StoneRise / Tech Posts
- Problem-first framing — explains pain point before solution
- Practical, benefit-focused language
- Invites engagement (comments, DMs) without being pushy
- Positions himself as practitioner, not salesman

